'''Ed Baird''' (born May 17, 1958) is an [[United States|American]] sailor. He was a coach of the [[1995 America's Cup]]-winning [[Team New Zealand]] and a [[helmsman]] for the [[2007 America's Cup]]-winning [[Alinghi]] syndicate.<ref name=sailworld>{{cite news|url=http://www.sail-world.com/usa/index.cfm?nid=35679&rid=4|title=A Great Week and a Great Year for Ed Baird|date=13 July 2007|work=sailworld.com|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref>

Growing up in Florida, Baird raced in the [[Optimist (dinghy)|Optimist]] class at junior level, before moving onto other dinghies. He won the World [[Laser (dinghy)|Laser]] Championships in 1980 and the World [[J/24]] Championships in 1983.<ref name="sailworld"/><ref name="americascup">{{cite web|url=http://32nd.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/circlinggalaxy/profil.php?idIndex=&idContent=5191|title=Ed Baird|work=32nd America's Cup: official website|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref>

==Coaching career==
Baird joined [[Team New Zealand]] as a coach for the [[1995 America's Cup]], guiding the syndicate to New Zealand's first ever Cup win. In the same year, he won the World Match Racing Championships,<ref name="americascup"/> and was named the [[US Sailor of the Year Awards|US's Yachtsman of the Year]].<ref name="ISAF">{{cite news|url=http://www.sailing.org/21232.php|title=Claire LEROY And Ed BAIRD Enter The Select Circle|date=7 November 2007|work=[[International Sailing Federation]]|accessdate=23 April 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430074244/http://www.sailing.org/21232.php|archivedate=30 April 2012|df=}}</ref>

In 1999, he skippered ''Young America'' in the Louis Vuitton series to determine the challenger for the following year's America's Cup, but the syndicate's challenge faltered when one of its two yachts nearly sank in a race against a Japanese team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/baird-crew-overboard-as-wave-hits-challenge-741498.html|title=Baird crew overboard as wave hits challenge|last=McFadden|first=Suzanne|date=10 November 1999|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref>

==Racing highlights==
Baird has also ventured into open water racing, having competed in [[Volvo Ocean Race|round the world races]] in 1997–98 (for ''[[Innovation Kvaerner]]'') and 2001–02 (for ''[[Djuice Dragons]]'').<ref name="americascup"/> As part of these offshore racing challenges, Baird was a member of the winning team in the grueling, Sydney to Hobart Race in 2000, aboard the maxi yacht, ''[[Nicorette II]]''.<ref>Lulham, Amanda, and James Breshnehan. "Sweden Smell of Success." ''Hobart Mercury'', 29 December 2000</ref>

As the [[helmsman]] of the [[Alinghi]] team for the [[2007 America's Cup]], he led the syndicate to win the series 5-2 against his former team, [[Team New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/2007-07-08-655804655_x.htm|title=Swiss celebrate return of America's Cup winner Alinghi|last=Engeler|first=Eliane|date=8 July 2007|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=23 April 2011}}</ref> Later in 2007, he was named the [[International Sailing Federation]]'s male [[ISAF World Sailor of the Year|World Sailor of the Year]].<ref name="ISAF"/>

Winning 4 of 5 events, Baird skippered Alinghi’s [[Extreme 40]] to a dominant win on the [[Extreme Sailing Series|iShares Extreme-40 Catamaran Circuit]] in 2008. He then coached team owner, [[Ernesto Bertarelli]], who helmed the massive catamaran, [[Alinghi 5]] in the [[2010 America's Cup]].

From 2011 to 2016, Baird skippered the US-flagged, Quantum Racing [[TP 52]] to win 4 seasons of the [[Audi MedCup]]/52 Super Series  and three TP 52 World Championships.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transpac 52 class - Quantum Racing|url=http://www.transpac52.org/teams/teams2008/quantum-racing.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520053026/http://www.transpac52.org/teams/teams2008/quantum-racing.html|archivedate=20 May 2014}}</ref> Baird currently races on international circuits for the TP 52 and [[RC 44]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rc44.com/teams/view/synergy_sailing_team|title=» Teams » RC Forty Four|author=OC Thirdpole|work=rc44.com}}</ref>

While best known as a champion match racer and fleet racing helmsman, Baird has also coached world and Olympic champions such as [[Anna Tunnicliffe]], Sally Barkow and [[Kevin Mahaney]].  He was a premier instructor for North-U’s Tactical and speed clinics in the 90’s, has written an instructional book (''Laser Racing'') and over a hundred tactical how-to articles.  Baird has worked with [[ESPN]], [[OLN|Outdoor Life Network]], [[NBC Sports Network|Versus]] and [[Television New Zealand]] as an expert commentator for shows about sailboat racing.

