The '''San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth''' ('''SAFOD''') is a research project begun in 2002 aimed at collecting geological data about the [[San Andreas Fault]] for the purpose of [[earthquake prediction|predicting]] and analyzing future [[earthquake]]s.<ref name="bbc20031205">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/3293947.stm |title=Project to drill into Earth fault |work=BBC News |first=Maggie |last=Shiels |date=December 5, 2003 |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2003/december3/safod-123.html |title=Stanford, U.S. Geological Survey team up to get inside scoop on quake zone San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth will permit researchers to collect temblor data 2.4 miles below surface of Earth |work=Stanford News |first=Mark |last=Shwartz |date=December 3, 2003 |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> The site consists of a {{convert|2.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} pilot hole and a {{convert|3.2|km|mi|abbr=on}} main hole.<ref name="quake.berk">{{cite web |url=http://www.quake.geo.berkeley.edu/safod/ |title=SAFOD (San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth) |work=Northern California Earthquake Data Center |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Located near the town of [[Parkfield, California]], the project has installed geophone sensors and GPS clocks in a borehole that cuts directly through the fault.<ref name="quake.berk" /> This data, along with samples collected during drilling, could shed new light on [[geochemistry|geochemical]] and mechanical properties around the fault zone.

SAFOD is part of [[Earthscope]], an Earth science program using geological and geophysical techniques to explore the structure of the North American continent and to understand the origin of earthquakes and volcanoes. Earthscope is funded by the [[National Science Foundation]] in conjunction with the [[United States Geological Survey|U.S. Geological Survey]] and [[NASA]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://earthquake.usgs.gov/research/parkfield/safod_pbo.php |title=San Andreas Fault Observatory at Depth |publisher=U.S. Geological Survey |accessdate=September 4, 2018}}</ref> Data collected at SAFOD are available from The Northern California Earthquake Data Center at [[University of California, Berkeley|U.C. Berkeley]] and at the [[IRIS Consortium|IRIS DMC]].

